BEGIN:VEVENT
SUMMARY:The Power of the Pin: Stories of the Moose Hide Campaign
DTSTART;TZID=America/Toronto:20260411T143000
DTEND;TZID=America/Toronto:20260411T163000
UID:blogto-232568@blogto.com
ATTACH;FMTTYPE=image/jpeg:https://blogto-production2-baselayer-display.blo
 gto.com/events/2026/03/23/original_imageeab4fd97-9952-4369-87cf-62a4d8cace
 d1.jpg
DESCRIPTION:The Power of the Pin: Stories of the Moose Hide Campaign\nFilm
  Screening of 2 Short Documentaries & Post-Film Q&A's\nDetails: Saturday\,
  April 11 at 2:30pm - Hot Docs Ted Rogers Cinema (506 Bloor St. W.\, Toron
 to\, ON)\nTickets: $25 - can be purchased on the Hot Docs website here: ht
 tps://boxoffice.hotdocs.ca/websales/pages/info.aspx?evtinfo=608203&showing
 =608315&\nFor too long\, the burden of not only experiencing Intimate Part
 ner Violence but also advocating to end it has rested on the shoulders of 
 women. When the Moose Hide Campaign began fifteen years ago\, it started w
 ith a simple but powerful question: Where are all the men in this vital wo
 rk?\nThe Moose Hide Campaign invites men and boys - and all Canadians - in
 to conversation about ending violence against women\, children and all tho
 se along the gender continuum. Setting aside shame and blame\, the movemen
 t calls people to healing journeys grounded in respect\, responsibility\, 
 and care for one another.\nAt the heart of the campaign is the gifting of 
 land-based medicine in the form of the moose hide pin. Gifted freely\, the
  pin represents a personal commitment to honour\, respect\, and protect wo
 men and children. Over the past fifteen years\, millions of pins have been
  shared across the country\, sparking countless conversations about how in
 dividuals and communities can work together to create safety.\nLast summer
 \, a film crew travelled through Ontario to explore what has happened when
  this land-based medicine meets people in their everyday lives. In two pow
 erful short documentaries\, they gathered the stories of two men whose liv
 es were changed after encountering the moose hide pin at critical moments 
 in their journeys. These films reveal deeply personal reflections on respo
 nsibility\, healing\, and the courage it takes to walk a different path. T
 ogether\, their stories explore how something as simple as a piece of moos
 e hide can open the door to transformation and accountability.\nThis speci
 al event premieres A Bridge Across and A Tree Remains in the home province
  where these stories take place. The afternoon brings together the men fea
 tured in the films\, the filmmakers who captured their journeys\, and memb
 ers of the Moose Hide Campaign family.\nThe gathering will include a scree
 ning of both films\, followed by a conversation with the documentary subje
 cts and the creative team. The event will also feature a ceremonial moment
  honouring the leadership and courage of the men whose stories are shared.
  All are invited to join this afternoon of storytelling\, reflection\, and
  community as the films explore the power of land-based medicine and the r
 ole each person can play in creating a future free from violence.\nThe Hot
  Docs Cinema is wheelchair accessible. For additional accessibility inquir
 ies\, please reach out to skoenig@mokwateh.com.
LOCATION:Hot Docs Ted Rogers Cinema
URL:https://www.blogto.com/events/the-power-of-the-pin-stories-of-the-moos
 e-hide-campaign-toronto/
X-SOURCE:blogTO
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
SUMMARY:Toronto Silent Film Festival: Just Kidding
DTSTART;TZID=America/Toronto:20260411T131500
DTEND;TZID=America/Toronto:20260411T150000
UID:blogto-232832@blogto.com
ATTACH;FMTTYPE=image/jpeg:https://blogto-production2-baselayer-display.blo
 gto.com/events/2026/03/28/original_imageb436fc4f-f733-4748-b6f4-04cba4db18
 85.jpg
DESCRIPTION:We're throwing this to the kids today with three comedies cent
 ered on the kids!\nFeaturing the masterpiece The Kid 1921 starring Chaplin
  and Jackie Coogan\n“The Little Tramp rescues an orphan baby from the st
 reets and raises him as his own. A miraculous pairing in this clever and i
 nnovative marriage of sentiment and slapstick\, a story of pancakes\, fist
 fights\, and dodging social services and policemen - as the opening title 
 card says\, “a picture with a smile - and perhaps a tear.” An instant 
 hit in 1921\, The Kid remains a masterwork of cinema.”-from Charlie Chap
 lin.com\nAnd once again\, Chaplin\, as The Little Tramp\, makes the statem
 ent about how family is one you make not necessarily the one you're born w
 ith.\nBrats 1930 -like you've never seen in close to a century--the SILENT
  version.\nIn a study of contrast with the Chaplin masterwork\, comes the 
 pure comic mayhem that only Laurel and Hardy can provide. All Stan and Oll
 ie want to do is spend a quiet evening at home playing checkers. Little Ol
 lie and little Stanley have other plans as they constantly interrupt the p
 eace with escalating chaos. We're sure many parents will relate. Screening
  materials courtesy of Kit Parker Films.\nBONUS: A secret short starring o
 ne of the top kid stars of the era--that will delight!\nLive Accompaniment
  by Jordan Klapman-please note: due to copyright requirements\, The Kid mu
 st be screened with the recorded soundtrack. Jordan will be playing live f
 or all other films.\nIntroduced by comedy programmer and Laurel & Hardy ex
 pert Chris Seguin.\nBring the kids (children 12 yrs and younger get in for
  free)\n$18 / $15 (seniors & under 25) Festival runs April 10-12
LOCATION:revue Cinema
URL:https://www.blogto.com/events/toronto-silent-film-festival-just-kiddin
 g-toronto/
X-SOURCE:blogTO
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
SUMMARY:Toronto Silent Film Festival: LOVE
DTSTART;TZID=America/Toronto:20260411T160000
DTEND;TZID=America/Toronto:20260411T180000
UID:blogto-232831@blogto.com
ATTACH;FMTTYPE=image/jpeg:https://blogto-production2-baselayer-display.blo
 gto.com/events/2026/03/28/original_imagee73990dc-9660-468a-be83-ef27ff2db8
 8e.jpg
DESCRIPTION:The love team of the 1920s-Swedish superstar Greta Garbo and A
 merican John Gilbert in their followup to the spectacular Flesh and the De
 vil.\nMeet special guest author Scott Reisfield\, great-nephew of Greta Ga
 rbo\, who will introduce the film and present a personal look at Garbo the
  woman through her personal letters.\nLive accompaniment by Laura Sgoi\nMG
 M's version of Tolstoy’s Anna Karenina was re-titled Love (1927) but it
 ’s possible that any story starring John Gilbert and Greta Garbo would h
 ave been given this title. When the off screen romance started in the Fles
 h and the Devil\, the movie magazines screaming headlines and breathless r
 eporting of their love affair made it impossible to do anything else. In t
 hat respect\, it was inevitable that Tolstoy's story would become heavily 
 modified. Garbo would star in the mid 1930s remake which restored the orig
 inal story. But here\, at the young age of 22\, Garbo was already celebrat
 ed not only for her beauty as a screen goddess but as a gifted artist. The
  resulting chemistry between Garbo and matinee idol John Gilbert glowed on
  film and they became a legendary couple both on and off the screen.\nTime
  wrote in December 1927\, “It isn’t Tolstoy\, but it is John Gilbert a
 nd Greta Garbo\, beautifully presented and magnificently acted.”\n$18 in
  advance or at the door. Festival runs April 10-12
LOCATION:Revue Cinema
URL:https://www.blogto.com/events/toronto-silent-film-festival-love-toront
 o/
X-SOURCE:blogTO
END:VEVENT
