BEGIN:VEVENT
SUMMARY:Elmer Iseler Singers present...The Earth Sings
DTSTART;TZID=America/Toronto:20260412T160000
DTEND;TZID=America/Toronto:20260412T180000
UID:blogto-233072@blogto.com
ATTACH;FMTTYPE=image/jpeg:https://blogto-production2-baselayer-display.blo
 gto.com/events/2026/04/02/original_imageb876bf8e-4e62-4099-afed-ea9ed70726
 f4.jpg
DESCRIPTION:A powerful choral journey connecting nature\, cosmos\, and the
  human spirit\nToronto\, ON — April 2026 — The Elmer Iseler Singers\, 
 under the direction of Lydia Adams\, C.M.\, present The Earth Sings\, an e
 vocative and timely concert exploring our relationship with the planet\, t
 he cosmos\, and one another.\nTaking place on Sunday\, April 12\, 2026 at 
 4:00 p.m. at Eglinton St. George’s United Church\, this program weaves t
 ogether contemporary masterworks\, Canadian voices\, and two world premier
 es in a deeply reflective musical experience.\nAudience members are also i
 nvited to a special pre-performance interview at 3:40 p.m. featuring compo
 sers Brad Barnham and Carmine Lappano\, offering insight into their newly 
 commissioned works and creative processes.\nAt the heart of the program is
  a meditation on Earth’s beauty and fragility. Works such as Earth Song 
 by Frank Ticheli offer a poignant plea for peace\, while Between the Alley
 s of the Stars by Edward Enman captures both awe and urgency in the face o
 f environmental change.\nThe concert also celebrates the vastness of the c
 osmos and humanity’s place within it. Audiences will experience luminous
  works by Ēriks Ešenvalds and R. Murray Schafer\, alongside the ethereal
  and the swallow by Caroline Shaw.\nA special highlight includes two world
  premieres:\n•	At That Hour by Brad Barnham (text by James Joyce)\n•	R
 emember Me by Carmine Lappano (text by Christina Rossetti)\nA central mome
 nt in the program is a tribute to pioneering Canadian composer Norma Beecr
 oft\, whose work The Living Flame of Love is featured. As co-founder of Ne
 w Music Concerts\, Beecroft played a transformative role in shaping Canada
 ’s contemporary music landscape and championing new voices.\nDavid Jaege
 r\, C.M. Canadian composer and retired Senior Producer at CBC and longtime
  advocate for Canadian composers\, reflects on the program’s impact:\n
 “It’s important for Canadian audiences to hear Canadian musical expres
 sion. The voices of our country’s composers are unique in the world of m
 usic and they resonate particularly strongly with Canadian listeners. They
  give expression to what it means to live in Canada.”\nSpeaking on Beecr
 oft’s legacy and the dedication\, Jaeger\, C.M. adds:\n“Norma was an i
 ntensely creative person with a passion to make music. She grew up in a fa
 mily of inventors and performers\, and had a knack for finding unique musi
 cal expressions and was fascinated by the range of mediums available to he
 r as a composer\, including choral music. All this distilled into a strong
  and expressive musical voice.”\nClosing the concert are radiant choral 
 works celebrating the beauty of the world and the human spirit\, including
  music by John Rutter\, Morten Lauridsen\, and Srul Irving Glick.\nWith fe
 atured soloists and the ensemble’s signature artistry\, The Earth Sings 
 invites audiences into a space of reflection\, connection\, and hope—rem
 inding us of the profound beauty of our shared home.\nEvent Details\nWhat:
  The Earth Sings\nWho: Elmer Iseler Singers\, Lydia Adams\, conductor\; Sh
 awn Grenke\, piano\nPre-Concert Talk: 3:40 p.m. with Brad Barnham and Carm
 ine Lappano\nWhen: Sunday\, April 12\, 2026 at 4:00 p.m.\nWhere: Eglinton 
 St. George’s United Church\, Toronto
LOCATION:Eglinton St. George's United Church
URL:https://www.blogto.com/events/elmer-iseler-singers-presentthe-earth-si
 ngs-toronto/
X-SOURCE:blogTO
END:VEVENT
