BEGIN:VEVENT
SUMMARY:Toronto Silent Film Festival: STRIKE! 1925
DTSTART;TZID=America/Toronto:20260412T131500
DTEND;TZID=America/Toronto:20260412T150000
UID:blogto-232829@blogto.com
ATTACH;FMTTYPE=image/jpeg:https://blogto-production2-baselayer-display.blo
 gto.com/events/2026/03/28/original_image13bc1ddc-b406-4b5f-9dcc-c8b67f1a99
 1d.jpg
DESCRIPTION:Toronto Silent Film Festival presents\, with live accompanimen
 t by Tania Gill\nThe Master Debuts an Agitprop Masterpiece.\nSergei Eisens
 tein’s Strike 1925 marks one of the most profound cinematic entrances in
  film history.\nIn telling the story of a 1903 strike\, triggered by the s
 uicide of a worker after an unjust accusation of theft\, and its brutal su
 ppression\, Eisenstein experimented using montage\, parallel editing\, exp
 anded time and intercutting of symbolic images to build the story and emot
 ion on an intertwined path with the characters. It would prove to be a com
 ing out as a director like no other\, and one that would change the look o
 f cinema and inspire directors for the next century.\nIt has all the seeds
  of his later works but the with an edginess that anchors the rawness of t
 he story. For many\, this first feature at age 26 years would remain his g
 reatest work\, surpassing even his other masterpiece Battleship Potemkin\,
  for sheer brilliance and power.
LOCATION:Revue Cinema
