BEGIN:VEVENT
SUMMARY:Book Launch: updn: 88 Spins with Bill Pechet by Leslie Van Duzer
DTSTART;TZID=America/Toronto:20260418T130000
DTEND;TZID=America/Toronto:20260418T150000
UID:blogto-233059@blogto.com
ATTACH;FMTTYPE=image/jpeg:https://blogto-production2-baselayer-display.blo
 gto.com/events/2026/04/02/original_imageb243bc07-7fa1-4580-adf6-308534a991
 8c.jpg
DESCRIPTION:Join us for the Toronto launch of updn: 88 Spins with Bill Pec
 het by Leslie Van Duzer.\nA book launch will be held April 18th from 1:00 
 p.m. to 3:00 p.m. at Swipe Design | Books + Objects\, 401 Richmond Street 
 West\, Toronto. The event is open to the public and free of charge.\nThere
  will be an exclusive interview by cultural historian and curator Michael 
 Prokopow with Bill Pechet and Leslie Van Duzer.\nBook Description\nDesigne
 r and artist\, teacher and mentor\, Bill Pechet has created a vast and var
 ied body of work: cemeteries\, residences\, illustrated children’s books
 \, street furniture\, sets and costumes for dance and theatre\, and many p
 ublic artworks\, both monumental and intimate. Whether a shade-dappled mem
 orial garden for infants\, or a beaker-shaped installation emitting mist a
 nd radiance in a library plaza\, a house set on an exquisite lot of sculpt
 ed Garry oaks\, or an eye-popping series of painted bunny-men\, his projec
 ts shine with the hallmarks of his vision—a sensitivity to environment\,
  a gentle irony\, an inexhaustible wellspring of originality.\nThis beguil
 ing testament to his cabinet of curiosity consciousness has been assembled
  and annotated with great insight\, attention and good humour by Leslie Va
 n Duzer. updn is complemented by contributions from renowned photographers
  Michael Perlmutter and Greg Girard among others\, and sketches and drawin
 gs from the Pechet Studio. Insightful essays and interviews speak to his h
 umanity and his work as a beloved teacher. Herein resides 88 proposals for
  rendering ideas material for those who wish to be challenged and charmed 
 by one of Canada’s most original and idiosyncratic artists.\nAbout the A
 uthor\nLeslie Van Duzer\, professor at the University of British Columbia\
 , has held academic positions in architecture schools across North America
 \, Europe and Japan. She has published numerous monographs on modern archi
 tecture and was lead editor of the series\, West Coast Modern Houses.
LOCATION:swipe design | books + objects
URL:https://www.blogto.com/events/book-launch-updn-88-spins-with-bill-pech
 et-by-leslie-van-duzer-toronto/
X-SOURCE:blogTO
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
SUMMARY:Bridgerton and Sound of Music-Inspired Waltz Lessons & Afternoon D
 ance Party
DTSTART;TZID=America/Toronto:20260418T140000
DTEND;TZID=America/Toronto:20260418T180000
UID:blogto-232466@blogto.com
ATTACH;FMTTYPE=image/jpeg:https://blogto-production2-baselayer-display.blo
 gto.com/events/2026/03/21/original_imaged89e2641-a59c-4592-8a21-d464b26d45
 b2.jpg
DESCRIPTION:Ever wanted to step into a scene from Bridgerton or dance like
  you’re in The Sound of Music? This Saturday afternoon waltz event hoste
 d by Waltz Toronto brings those iconic\, romantic styles to life—no expe
 rience or partner required.\nLearn the elegance and flow of traditional wa
 ltz as seen in Regency-era ballrooms and classic film scenes\, including t
 he charming Laendler (featured in The Sound of Music) and more recently Wa
 ltz in the style of the Bridgerton TV series. These beginner-friendly less
 ons are designed to be fun\, relaxed\, and easy to follow—perfect if you
 ’ve never tried partner dancing before.\nThe afternoon starts with two e
 ngaging lessons\, including the ever-popular cross-step waltz (known for i
 ts smooth\, graceful feel)\, followed by a social dance where you can prac
 tice your new moves in a welcoming\, low-pressure environment.\nWhether yo
 u're a fan of period dramas\, love vintage-inspired experiences\, or just 
 want a unique Saturday activity\, this event offers a chance to dance\, co
 nnect\, and feel like you’ve stepped into another era.\nEvent Details:\n
 📍 St. Barnabas (175 Hampton Ave)\n🗓 Saturday\, April 18\n🕑 2:00pm
  – 6:10pm\nSchedule:\n• 2:00pm – 2:50pm: Cross-step Waltz (beginner-
 friendly\, slow tempo)\n• 2:50pm – 4:10pm: Traditional Waltz (Bridgert
 on & Sound of Music-inspired Laendler style)\n• 4:15pm – 6:10pm: Socia
 l Waltz Dance Party\nGood to know:\n• No partner or experience required\
 n• Absolute beginners welcome\n• Lessons are different each time\nInst
 ructors & Music:\nTaught by Simon Threlkeld & Cheryl Henry\nMusic by DJ Si
 mon\nPrice: $28 includes lessons and the dance\n$20 for Students with ID
URL:https://www.blogto.com/events/bridgerton-and-sound-of-music-inspired-w
 altz-lessons-afternoon-dance-party-toronto/
X-SOURCE:blogTO
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
SUMMARY:Celebrating Indigenous Feminist Poets
DTSTART;TZID=America/Toronto:20260418T190000
DTEND;TZID=America/Toronto:20260418T210000
UID:blogto-232952@blogto.com
ATTACH;FMTTYPE=image/jpeg:https://blogto-production2-baselayer-display.blo
 gto.com/events/2026/03/31/original_image27d5b7b1-5b4c-41db-926a-7227d454c2
 ad.jpg
DESCRIPTION:REGISTER HERE: https://www.eventbrite.com/e/celebrating-indige
 nous-feminist-poets-tickets-1985320280402?utm-campaign=social&utm-content=
 attendeeshare&utm-medium=discovery&utm-term=listing&utm-source=cp&aff=ebds
 shcopyurl\nJoin us on Zoom for the 4th annual National Poetry Month readin
 g organized by the Feminist Caucus of the League of Canadian Poets!\nThis 
 year\, we’re honoured to feature 11 outstanding Indigenous feminist poet
 s. Each will give a 5-minute live reading. There’ll be a short break in 
 the middle and a question period at the end.\nBuy tickets on Eventbrite to
 day! Please pay what you can\, as a limited number of tickets are availabl
 e at each price point: $0\, $5\, $10\, and $20. All the money goes to the 
 poets!\nTo request a need-based free ticket (if the $0 tickets sell out)\,
  please email feministcaucus@leaguepoets.com\nPoster by Mary Simmerling\nO
 riginal artwork by Nathalie Coutou\nThis event is sponsored in part by the
  League of Canadian Poets and the Canada Council for the Arts\nReader Bios
  (Alphabetical)\nKarrie Auger is a nêhiyaw-ayisiyiniw (Cree person). She 
 is a member of Bigstone Cree Nation\, and lives and loves with the land ca
 lled amiskwaciy. Her poetry is a practice of relational dream-weaving. Thr
 ough an embodied non-linear Indigenous poetics\, she dreams herself and he
 r relations\, into collective experiences\, where relational possibility e
 merges for all our relations.\nLeah Baptiste is a Sahtú Dene and Ukrainia
 n poet. She is a member of Délı̨nę First Nation (Treaty 11) living in 
 Edmonton (Treaty 6). Her work has been included in Room Magazine\, oteh n
 îkân\, and she has received an Indigenous Voices Award for Unpublished P
 oetry.\nCassandra Blanchard was born in the Yukon and is a part of the Sel
 kirk First Nation. Her book of poetry “Fresh Pack of Smokes” won the 2
 020 ReLit Award. She resides in Duncan\, Vancouver Island.\nMolly Cross-Bl
 anchard (she/her) is a white and Métis writer\, editor\, and teacher born
  in Treaty 3 (Fort Frances\, ON)\, raised in Treaty 6 (Prince Albert\, SK)
 \, and currently living in Treaty 1 (Winnipeg\, MB). Molly’s full-lengt
 h book of poetry is “Exhibitionist” (Coach House Books\, 2021).\nMetis
  poet\, writer\, and Professor Marilyn Dumont teaches for the faculties of
  Arts and Native Studies at the University of Alberta and is proud of Meti
 s family lines from her Mother’s - Vaness / Dufresne families and her fa
 ther’s - Boudreau/Dumont families.\nShe was awarded the 2018 Lifetime Me
 mbership from the League of Canadian Poets for her contributions to poetry
  in Canada. In 2019\, she received the University of Alberta Distinguished
  Alumni Award and the Alberta Lieutenant Governor’s Distinguished Artist
  Award\, and in 2022 was Awarded the Alberta Queen’s Platinum Jubilee me
 dal for public service.\nHer four collections of poetry have won provincia
 l or national awards: “A Really Good Brown Girl” (1996)\; “green gir
 l dreams Mountains” (2001)\; “that tongued belonging” (2007)\; “Th
 e Pemmican Eaters” (2015).  A fifth collection surrounding Indigenous hi
 story of Edmonton\, called “South Side of a Kinless River” was publish
 ed by Brick Books in 2024.\nLiz Howard is a settler/Anishinaabe poet\, edi
 tor\, and educator. Her critically acclaimed works include the Griffin Poe
 try Prize winning Infinite Citizen of the Shaking Tent and Letters in a Br
 uised Cosmos. Born and raised in Northern Ontario on Treaty 9 territory\, 
 she now lives in Tiohtià:ke/Montréal.\nsakâw laboucan (they/them) is an
  amiskwaciywaskahikan-based poet\, singer\, and member of the Woodland Cre
 e First Nation. They are a PhD student in Indigenous Studies at the Univer
 sity of Alberta studying nehiyaw queer feminist governance. They are named
  after the deep green of the northern forest aka the bush.\nCarley Lizotte
  (she/her) is a nêhiyaw-otipemisiwak storyteller\, poet\, creative and ed
 ucator. She was born and raised in Fort Vermilion\, and is currently based
  in amiskwâciwaskihikan. Her poetry is a reflection of who and where she 
 comes from. She sees writing as a form of ceremony.\nWiingashk Wâhkôôm 
 “Sweetgrass Lodge” (Government name: Jen Murphy) is an enrolled member
  of the Chippewa-Cree Nation of Rocky Boy\, Montana\, and brings a powerfu
 l cultural and systemic perspective to Building Blue’s work. She holds a
  degree in Communications and a Master’s Certificate in Native American 
 Studies\, and has spent her career working in child protection\, adult par
 ole\, and Indigenous advocacy. Jen began her career as a Child Protection 
 Specialist\, later serving as an ICWA Expert for the State of Montana. She
  went on to work in Adult Felony Parole\, gaining hands-on experience in r
 ehabilitation\, accountability\, and public safety. A passionate advocate 
 for Missing and Murdered Indigenous Women and People (MMIW/P)\, Jen leads 
 Tveraa Photography\, a project that brings visibility to MMIW/P through a 
 national photo series of Native women featured on billboards across the co
 untry. The project has been showcased on NBC’s Today Show and CBS’s 48
  Hours\, and inspired her award-winning short film “Not Afraid\,” whic
 h she executive produced. Jen serves by appointment of the Montana Attorne
 y General on both the Native American Domestic Violence Fatality Review Co
 mmission and the State Domestic Violence Fatality Review Commission.\nanni
 e ross is a teacher/painter working in/with/along the Canadian west\nDéla
 ni Valin is a Métis writer. Her first book was “Shapeshifters” (Nigh
 twood Editions\, 2022). Her poetry has been awarded The Malahat Review’
 s Long Poem Prize and subTerrain’s Lush Triumphant Award\, and has ap
 peared in PRISM International\, Adbusters\, Room\, and elsewhere. She is
  on the editorial board of The Malahat Review.\nFEMINIST CAUCUS MISSION S
 TATEMENT\nAdopted November\, 2022\nThe Feminist Caucus of the League of Ca
 nadian Poets strongly and uncompromisingly champions the rights of those w
 ho identify as women and/or feminists in Canada and worldwide. Our mandate
  is to celebrate\, promote\, and support women’s creativity within the L
 eague and beyond. We oppose systemic misogyny\, anti-feminist traditions\,
  and rights-restrictive cultural relativism and commit to take action agai
 nst any infringement of women's rights and their creative work. The Femini
 st Caucus respects and advocates for equality and freedom of expression in
  its practices and membership.
LOCATION:Virtual Event
URL:https://www.blogto.com/events/celebrating-indigenous-feminist-poets-to
 ronto/
X-SOURCE:blogTO
END:VEVENT
