BEGIN:VEVENT
SUMMARY:Laalima\, The In-Between Supper\, by Rashmi Singh of Spoonful with
  Rashmi
DTSTART;TZID=America/Toronto:20260418T183000
DTEND;TZID=America/Toronto:20260418T210000
UID:blogto-229362@blogto.com
ATTACH;FMTTYPE=image/jpeg:https://blogto-production2-baselayer-display.blo
 gto.com/events/2026/01/18/original_image9c6b503a-8716-43da-aed6-bc0c874d29
 8f.jpg
DESCRIPTION:This dinner lives in the in-between. Between seasons and memor
 ies. Between Bihar and Canada. Tonight we honour both our Canadian homelan
 d and the rustic\, bold flavours of Bihar - a northeastern state in India 
 where mustard takes centre stage\, garlic is never held back\, and fennel 
 sweetens the finish. It is a celebration of the food the chef grew up with
  and what grows here now.\nLaalima brings together Bihari classics and sea
 sonal Canadian spring produce\, reimagined with care but never removed fro
 m their roots. Inspired by summers at the chef's Nani’s hill-station hom
 e\, this supper honours food that was slow\, thoughtful\, and deeply nouri
 shing—meant to be shared\, not rushed.\nWith this dinner\, Rashmi invite
 s you to return to a grandmother’s home and to the quiet joy of being so
  loved that someone made your favourite food before you even asked.\n----\
 nSTARTERS\nAsparagus Chaat\nA spring opening\, chaat-style. Crisply fried 
 asparagus layered over whipped yogurt\, lifted with tangy tamarind\, green
  chutney\, and a warmth from garlic chilli crisps. Comforting flavours rei
 magined through textural contrast.\nCreamy Daal Pitthi\nA modern tribute t
 o Bihar’s steamed dumpling tradition. Soft dumplings made with wheat and
  black chickpea flour are gently simmered in a rich\, creamy lentil base\,
  delicately spiced and finished with crunchy garlic crumbs\, and bright ci
 trus. A Bihari staple in spirit\, this bowl offers warmth\, nourishment\, 
 and the quiet reassurance of home.\nMAINS\nBasanti Bhuna Saag\nA celebrati
 on of spring greens\, cooked the Bihari way. Mustard greens\, dandelions\,
  spinach\, and kale are slow cooked into a creamy\, earthy\, balanced\, an
 d grounding dish. Finished with crisp fried leek ribbons and golden garlic
  chips for texture and contrast.\nBharwa Paanch Phoran Sabzi\nClassic stuf
 fing\, bold flavours. Potatoes\, eggplants\, and tomatoes are stuffed with
  a traditional panch phoran (five spice) mixture — aromatic\, robust\, a
 nd unmistakably Eastern Indian.\nSIDES\nBhaat\nSteamed short-grain rice wi
 th a dollop of ghee\nAjwain Paratha\nWheat flour flatbreads seasoned with 
 carrom and onion seeds\nSirka Pyaaz\nPickled shallots\nMooli Dhaniya\nRadi
 sh and Cilantro chutney\nDESSERT\nGud ki Kheer & Thekua\nA gentle\, nostal
 gic closer. A creamy rice pudding\, infused with cardamom\, and sweetened 
 with jaggery. It's topped with a delicate\, crisp thekua wafer\, a nod to 
 Bihar’s beloved festival biscuit. Guests must crack through the wafer to
  uncover the pudding beneath — a playful\, nostalgic finale that bridges
  tradition and surprise.\n----\nRashmi Singh is an Executive events and co
 mmunications specialist based in Toronto — a storyteller at heart\, both
  in her work and in her kitchen. She was raised on the warmth of her Nani 
 & Ma’s Bihari cooking. She now shares those memories and flavours throug
 h her culinary Instagram page\, Spoonful with Rashmi.\nLaalima is her debu
 t supper club — a heartfelt tribute to the food of her childhood and the
  woman who inspired it all. With every course\, Rashmi invites guests to e
 xperience not just a menu but a memory of garlic-scented kitchens\, steel 
 plates clinking\, and favourites made before you even asked.
LOCATION:The Depanneur
URL:https://www.blogto.com/events/laalima-the-in-between-supper-by-rashmi-
 singh-of-spoonful-with-rashmi-toronto/
X-SOURCE:blogTO
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
SUMMARY:LATE NIGHT FCKERY APRIL GOLDEN SHOWERS
DTSTART;TZID=America/Toronto:20260418T230000
DTEND;TZID=America/Toronto:20260418T235900
