BEGIN:VEVENT
SUMMARY:Poetry Reading and Open Mic - Crossing Lines: Poets Who Came to Ca
 nada in the Vietnam War Era
DTSTART;TZID=America/Toronto:20260418T150000
DTEND;TZID=America/Toronto:20260418T170000
UID:blogto-232926@blogto.com
ATTACH;FMTTYPE=image/jpeg:https://blogto-production2-baselayer-display.blo
 gto.com/events/2026/03/31/original_imagec95fba95-67d2-48b2-b816-e34abda142
 b7.jpg
DESCRIPTION:In a time marked by escalating war\, violence\, and global unc
 ertainty\, poetry continues to offer a language for conscience\, resistanc
 e\, and refuge.\nPoets Edward Baranosky\, Sue Chenette\, Roger Greenwald\,
  Barry Olshen\, John Reibetanz and Allen\nSutterfield will read from their
  contributions to the anthology Crossing Lines: Poets Who Came to Canada i
 n the Vietnam War Era.\nEach attendee will receive a copy of the anthology
 .\nTheir lives were shaped by a profound historical choice: each left the 
 United States during the Vietnam War era as a conscientious objector. In r
 efusing to participate in war\, they crossed borders—geographical\, poli
 tical\, and moral—and found new homes in Canada. Their writing carries t
 he imprint of that decision: poems shaped by exile and belonging\, protest
  and quiet witness\, rupture and renewal.\nThrough readings\, reflection\,
  and conversation\, this gathering honours not only their artistic contrib
 utions but also the enduring role of poetry in times of conflict. These vo
 ices remind us that art can hold complexity where slogans cannot\, and tha
 t dissent—expressed with care and craft—can become part of a country
 ’s cultural inheritance.\nAfter the readers there will be an open mic on
  the theme of war and peace.\nThis is an opportunity to listen deeply\, to
  remember\, and to imagine how language might still guide us toward more h
 umane futures
LOCATION:Hirut
URL:https://www.blogto.com/events/poetry-reading-and-open-mic-crossing-lin
 es-poets-who-came-to-canada-in-the-vietnam-war-era-toronto/
X-SOURCE:blogTO
END:VEVENT
