BEGIN:VEVENT
SUMMARY:Block Printing on Fabric: Tote Bag Workshop
DTSTART;TZID=America/Toronto:20260425T103000
DTEND;TZID=America/Toronto:20260425T133000
UID:blogto-233013@blogto.com
ATTACH;FMTTYPE=image/jpeg:https://blogto-production2-baselayer-display.blo
 gto.com/events/2026/04/01/original_image32e76337-9eeb-4cfe-a0db-ff1ec37075
 bf.jpg
DESCRIPTION:t's springtime and that means it's market season! Design your 
 own tote bag to use for all the essentials this year.\nOverview\nLearn the
  fundamentals of block printing on fabric in this hands-on\, beginner-frie
 ndly workshop. Artist\, Sarah Aranha\, will share her inspiration and demo
 nstrate the essential techniques before guiding you step-by-step through t
 he full process.\nParticipants will design and carve their own linoleum bl
 ock\, learn how to properly set up a printing area\, and print their desig
 n onto a fabric tote bag. You’ll leave with a finished tote bag and your
  carved block\, giving you the tools and confidence to continue experiment
 ing at home.\nNo prior experience required. All materials provided.\nWhat 
 to expect\nOur retail space opens at 10AM\, with the workshop beginning 10
 :30AM. All materials will be set out for participants. Sarah will guide yo
 u though a hands-on session. Leave with a fabulous tote and your own block
  to print again and again!\nAbout your instructor\nSarah Aranha is an arti
 st and maker who works with watercolour\, gouache and textiles. Her work d
 raws from the patterns\, interactions and routines of the everyday. A skil
 led arts facilitator\, Sarah regularly teaches block printing\, still life
  drawing\, and watercolour at studios and organizations such as Hot Pizza 
 Studio\, The Bentway\, MOCA\, Foodshare\, and others. She lives and works 
 in Toronto.\n@sarah.aranha / saraharanha.com\nHow to get here\nWe are at C
 ollege and Spadina. The 506 and 510 streetcar are the closest options. At 
 College\, just head South on Spadina. You will find us on the West side at
  448 Spadina Avenue.\nLimited street parking is available.
LOCATION:Gwartzman's Art Supplies
URL:https://www.blogto.com/events/block-printing-on-fabric-tote-bag-worksh
 op-toronto/
X-SOURCE:blogTO
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
SUMMARY:Blood on the Clocktower at Royal Game Cafe in Richmond Hill
DTSTART;TZID=America/Toronto:20260425T190000
DTEND;TZID=America/Toronto:20260425T213000
UID:blogto-232896@blogto.com
ATTACH;FMTTYPE=image/jpeg:https://blogto-production2-baselayer-display.blo
 gto.com/events/2026/03/30/original_image1a89f80a-3b1f-4cf9-898f-1ad9392769
 dc.jpg
DESCRIPTION:Whether you're a seasoned gamer or new to the world of social 
 deception games\, this event offers something for everyone. Come solo or w
 ith friends and immerse yourself in a game of Blood on the Clocktower. Our
  events are a great way to connect with members of local communities and a
 re perfect for folks arriving in Toronto looking to make new connections.\
 nWhat is Blood on the Clocktower? - Blood on the Clocktower is an advanced
  version of the game Werewolf\, where crucially\, the dead still have an i
 mportant role to play in the game. The game is run by a Storyteller who ha
 s carefully crafted an experience and facilitates the game for up to 20 pl
 ayers. It is part deduction and part deception. Set in the town of Ravensw
 ood Bluff\, players in the game assume different roles\, each with unique 
 abilities to hunt down evil or manipulate the townsfolk.\nThanks to the ge
 nerosity of the Royal Game Cafe\, we will be taking over their semi-privat
 e room for a delightfully fun night of Blood on the Clocktower! Royal Game
  Cafe has a full menu of food and both alcoholic and non-alcoholic drink o
 ptions to choose from. Tickets are $20 for the night or $13.50 for Changel
 ing Special Events Members.\nIf you have not played before or are newer to
  the game\, there will be a quick tutorial at the top of the event to lear
 n how to play and ask any questions from the Storyteller.\nWe will be play
 ing Trouble Brewing at this event.\nAge recommendation\, 16 years +\nTo le
 arn more\, find Changeling Gaming Events Toronto on Eventbrite or click th
 e website link to see this event (see right side on desktop/above on mobil
 e).
LOCATION:Royal Game Cafe
URL:https://www.blogto.com/events/blood-on-the-clocktower-at-royal-game-ca
 fe-in-richmond-hill-toronto/
X-SOURCE:blogTO
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
SUMMARY:Book Launch: Hidden Toronto by Dave LeBlanc
DTSTART;TZID=America/Toronto:20260425T160000
DTEND;TZID=America/Toronto:20260425T180000
UID:blogto-233060@blogto.com
ATTACH;FMTTYPE=image/jpeg:https://blogto-production2-baselayer-display.blo
 gto.com/events/2026/04/02/original_imagef5e2b387-b977-423f-900e-01c0bab979
 39.jpg
DESCRIPTION:Join us for the launch of Hidden Toronto: Secret Places and Fo
 rgotten Gems of Toronto and the GTA by Dave LeBlanc\nA book launch will be
  held April 25th from 4:00 p.m. to 6:00 p.m. at Swipe Design | Books + Obj
 ects\, 401 Richmond Street West\, Toronto. The event is open to the public
  and free of charge.\nBook Description\nHidden Toronto: Secret Places and 
 Forgotten Gems of Toronto and the GTA is an entertaining guide to the Grea
 ter Toronto Area (GTA)\, unveiling its hidden or often-overlooked gems in 
 the forms of buildings\, neighborhoods\, artworks\, building materials and
  much more -- places\, objects and topics that might not be covered in a r
 egular travel guide to Toronto but that have fascinating and important sto
 ries that inform the larger story of the city.\nOrganized by theme\, the b
 ook includes chapters on signage and logos\, buildings\, neighborhoods\, i
 nfrastructure\, artworks and objects\, and trails and other places. In tot
 al the book has 48 stories\, often with multiple hidden places or things d
 iscussed in each. Accompanying the vibrant text are both recent photos tak
 en in the last year as well as historical images from city archives and co
 llections that illustrate the history and give a modern perspective to eac
 h story.\nHidden Toronto will open up your curiosity about the city and th
 e many things we take for granted when we live\, work and visit there. By 
 the end\, you'll be an enlightened "Architourist\," scoping out old signs\
 , romping down forgotten paths and swooning over architectural details tha
 t help make Toronto the fascinating place it is.\nAbout the Author\nDave L
 eBlanc writes weekly as “The Architourist” for the The Globe and Mail.
  While other kids were trading hockey cards\, Dave was charting the progre
 ss of the CN Tower\, and he’s been an architecture lover and Toronto adv
 ocate ever since.\nDave attended Wexford School for the Arts\, Toronto Met
 ropolitan University and York University. He worked in radio from 1988 - 2
 024 and has written for Globe Real Estate since 2003. An authority on Mode
 rnist architecture (1945-80)\, Dave attended “Conserving the Modern” i
 n 2005 and 2007 (Canada)\, Palm Springs’ Modernism Week (multiple times)
 \, and architectural conferences in the Netherlands and Spain. He has serv
 ed as a juror for the Ontario Association of Architects and the City of To
 ronto.\nDave’s work has also appeared Spacing\, Canadian Architect\, Can
 adian Interiors and Wallpaper. In 2014-15 he hosted Where Cool Came From\,
  a television program on pop culture. His first novel\, Falconi’s Tracto
 r\, was released 2019.
LOCATION:swipe design | books + objects
URL:https://www.blogto.com/events/book-launch-hidden-toronto-by-dave-lebla
 nc-toronto/
X-SOURCE:blogTO
END:VEVENT
