BEGIN:VEVENT
SUMMARY:In the Light of the Machine: Toward a Relational Ethics of AI
DTSTART;TZID=America/Toronto:20260508T120000
DTEND;TZID=America/Toronto:20260508T140000
UID:blogto-232944@blogto.com
ATTACH;FMTTYPE=image/jpeg:https://blogto-production2-baselayer-display.blo
 gto.com/events/2026/03/31/original_image1f3018a0-1132-496f-a16a-4dd0dcfa7b
 ef.jpg
DESCRIPTION:As AI systems become increasingly entangled with our cultural\
 , economic\, and ecological worlds\, how do we negotiate an ethical landsc
 ape of emergent intelligence? Moving beyond familiar debates over risk and
  safety\, this conversation brings together panelists who will explore how
  art can help us sense\, critique\, and reimagine the systems shaping our 
 technological present. By situating AI within broader epistemological and 
 cultural contexts. Moderated by Lisa Deanne Smith\, this panel seeks to ex
 pand AI discourse and understand machine learning as a site of relation.\n
 In the Light of the Machine: Toward a Relational Ethics of Artificial Inte
 lligence coincides with Onsite Gallery’s current exhibition Becoming (in
  the light of the miracle) guest curated by Farah Yusuf.\nAlso on view at 
 Onsite Gallery are The Delaney Family Emerging Curator’s Prize: Metaboli
 c Loop and Diego Santamaría (HIDROCK) | The Shared Flight (2025)\nBecomin
 g (in the light of the miracle) is on view at Onsite Gallery until May 16\
 , 2026\nBecoming (in the light of the miracle) is generously supported by 
 the Ontario Arts Council\, an agency of the Government of Ontario through 
 the Curatorial Projects: Indigenous and Culturally Diverse program.\nOnsit
 e Gallery is generously supported by The Delaney Family
LOCATION:Virtual Event
URL:https://www.blogto.com/events/in-the-light-of-the-machine-toward-a-rel
 ational-ethics-of-ai-toronto/
X-SOURCE:blogTO
END:VEVENT
