BEGIN:VEVENT
SUMMARY:IMAGES AT AN EXHIBITION
DTSTART;TZID=America/Toronto:20260516T200000
DTEND;TZID=America/Toronto:20260516T220000
UID:blogto-231313@blogto.com
ATTACH;FMTTYPE=image/jpeg:https://blogto-production2-baselayer-display.blo
 gto.com/events/2026/02/23/original_imagecdb7fceb-9c9f-467d-87aa-5574a64636
 1b.jpg
DESCRIPTION:Zoltán Kodály’s Háry János suite contains music extracte
 d from Kodály’s opera of the same name\, which tells the story of Háry
  János\, “a peasant\, a veteran soldier who day after day sits at the t
 avern spinning yarns about his heroic exploits.” The world premiere of A
 lice Ping Yee Ho’s Concerto for piano and orchestra follows\; this work 
 is subtitled “Pictures from an Imaginary Exhibition” (a nod to Mussorg
 sky’s Pictures at an Exhibition) and is inspired by paintings by contemp
 orary artists Wesley Tongson and Christina Petrowska Quilico\, who also pe
 rforms the solo piano part. The concert concludes with Anton Bruckner’s 
 Symphony no. 8\, the last symphony that Bruckner completed. The symphony b
 egins with a subdued opening that music theorist Heinrich Schenker describ
 es as “like the beginning of the world\,” before launching into the ma
 in theme proper. The final movement contains many recurrences of themes fr
 om the previous three movements\, creating a uniquely unified symphonic wo
 rk.\nKristian Alexander | conductor\nChristina Petrowska Quilico | pianist
 \nMark Wigmore | host (Classical 96.3 FM)\n7:10 p.m. Prélude: pre-concert
  recital.\n7:20 p.m. Pre-concert talk.\nIntermission discussion and Q&A wi
 th Christina Petrowska Quilico and Daniel Vnukowski.
LOCATION:Meridian Arts Centre
URL:https://www.blogto.com/events/images-at-an-exhibition-toronto/
X-SOURCE:blogTO
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
SUMMARY:Lulaworld 2026: David Labrada's DLM Salsa Groove Collective w DJ S
 isco
DTSTART;TZID=America/Toronto:20260516T203000
DTEND;TZID=America/Toronto:20260517T030000
UID:blogto-233449@blogto.com
ATTACH;FMTTYPE=image/jpeg:https://blogto-production2-baselayer-display.blo
 gto.com/events/2026/04/10/original_image13f2a1bf-ae93-4887-b97d-6fa1f124dd
 c1.jpg
DESCRIPTION:Lulaworld Festival (May 11 to 17)\nJoin us at Lula Lounge to c
 elebrate the 20th annual Lulaworld festival\, marking two decades of local
  and international jazz\, Latin\, Brazilian\, soul and folk from around th
 e globe and around the corner.\nCanada’s premier Latin music and dance c
 lub invites you to experience an unforgettable night of salsa — dinner\,
  dancing\, and live music all under one roof!\nBook a table for dinner and
  dancing\, or arrive after 9 PM to head straight to the dance floor.\nEven
 ing Schedule\n� 7:00 PM – Doors open for dinner and drinks\n� 9:00 P
 M – Salsa lesson with Teria Morada(no partner needed!)\n� 10:00 PM –
  First live salsa set\, with a second set at midnight\n� 11:00 PM – Ke
 ep the energy going with DJ Sisco spinning Top 40\, salsa\, and Latin hits
 \nAbout the Band\nAdonis Puentes is a Cuban-born\, Canadian-based artist w
 hose music blends traditional Cuban roots with contemporary global influen
 ces\, creating a rich\, rhythmic sound centred on themes of love\, life\, 
 and cultural connection. A Grammy-nominated vocalist and internationally t
 ouring performer\, he has released critically acclaimed albums such as Vid
 a\, Sabor a Café\, and Dicen\, showcasing his poetic songwriting and expr
 essive vocals. Known for both intimate compositions and vibrant\, danceabl
 e arrangements\, Puentes continues to evolve his sound through collaborati
 ons with top Latin musicians\, most recently on his upcoming 2026 album A 
 Buscar mi Suerte\, a dynamic\, orchestral project that highlights his sign
 ature warmth and passion.\nWhy Lula is unique:\nThe only venue of its kind
  in North America\, Lula Lounge features a rotating roster of more than a 
 dozen full salsa orchestras every Friday and Saturday—year-round. Our st
 age welcomes the best local talent alongside special guests from across Ca
 nada and the Americas\, offering a one-of-a-kind salsa experience in a war
 m\, colourful\, and inclusive space.
LOCATION:Lula Lounge
URL:https://www.blogto.com/events/lulaworld-2026-david-labradas-dlm-salsa-
 groove-collective-w-dj-sisco-toronto/
X-SOURCE:blogTO
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
SUMMARY:Painting the Seasons - A Pipa Solo Concert
DTSTART;TZID=America/Toronto:20260516T140000
DTEND;TZID=America/Toronto:20260516T150000
UID:blogto-231881@blogto.com
ATTACH;FMTTYPE=image/jpeg:https://blogto-production2-baselayer-display.blo
 gto.com/events/2026/03/07/original_imaged9ab1bbb-72cf-4c3f-a5e1-4031d8f9b6
 84.jpg
DESCRIPTION:Internationally renowned and Toronto-based Pipa artist Wen Zha
 o\, performs on the ancient Chinese instrument\, the Pipa\, a plucked inst
 rument similar to the lute\, with over 2\,000 years of history\, introduce
 d through the ancient Silk Road from Central Asia and becoming one of the 
 most significant solo instruments in musical history.\nThis solo concert c
 elebrates China's rich musical legacy with a traditional and folk music re
 pertoire spanning across dynasties\, painting a vivid picture of our natur
 al landscape through the four seasons and classical poetry songs. Wen will
  also talk about some traditional Chinese Festivals\, such as the Lunar Ne
 w Year and Dragon Boat festivals.\nFree admission. Registration required. 
 Register online\, in-person\, or by phone at (416) 394-5120.
LOCATION:Toronto Public Library - Richview Branch
URL:https://www.blogto.com/events/painting-the-seasons-a-pipa-solo-concert
 -toronto/
X-SOURCE:blogTO
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
SUMMARY:Panel Discussion: Toronto's Urban / Nature Ab-uses
DTSTART;TZID=America/Toronto:20260516T140000
DTEND;TZID=America/Toronto:20260516T150000
UID:blogto-233048@blogto.com
ATTACH;FMTTYPE=image/jpeg:https://blogto-production2-baselayer-display.blo
 gto.com/events/2026/04/02/original_imagecb4f2d23-e4ea-407a-89b5-be6ec805db
 96.jpg
DESCRIPTION:About artist Gillian Iles's Glorious Catastrophe\, writer Rui 
 Pimenta describes: "The dualities present in the exhibition speak to a wor
 ld in division\, while capturing a suspended moment in which outcomes are 
 yet to be determined\, and an opportunity for something different or bette
 r remains in the air." For more information about the exhibition: https://
 www.kofflerarts.org/whatson/exhibitions/exhibition/glorious-catastrophe-gi
 llian-iles\nTo explore "a world in division\," this panel discussion focus
 es on the fluidity of urban spaces in Toronto. Rapid development and expan
 sion have resulted in uses/abuses of the environment and reduced the avail
 ability of free-use third spaces. This domination of nature and commodific
 ation of third spaces\, leaves inhabitants with less leisure and places gr
 eater pressure on the unhoused. What opportunities exist to advocate for a
 daptive\, sustainable approaches to managing these ever-evolving spaces?\n
 Moderator: Shawn Micallef is the author of Frontier City: Toronto on the V
 erge of Greatness (2017)\, The Trouble With Brunch: Work Class and the Pur
 suit of Leisure (2014) and Full Frontal TO: Exploring Toronto’s Vernacul
 ar Architecture (2012). The updated and expanded edition of his first book
 \, Stroll: Psychogeographic Walking Tours of Toronto\, was published in 20
 24. He’s a Toronto Star columnist\, civics instructor at University of T
 oronto\, and a Senior Fellow at Massey College where he was also a 2011-20
 12 Southam Journalism Fellow. Shawn is a co-founder of Spacing\, a magazin
 e about Canadian cities and urban issues.\nPanelists:\nJennifer Bonnell is
  a professor in the Department of History at York University\, where she t
 eaches courses in Canadian\, environmental and public history. She is the 
 author or co-editor of four books\, including Stewards of Splendour: A His
 tory of Wildlife and People in British Columbia (2023) and Reclaiming the 
 Don: An Environmental History of Toronto’s Don River Valley (2024\, 2nd 
 ed.). Her current book project\, Foragers of a Modern Countryside: Honeybe
 es\, Environmental Change\, and Beekeeper Advocacy in the Great Lakes Regi
 on\, will be published by the University of Washington Press’s Weyerhaeu
 ser Environmental Books series.\nMaggie Helwig (she/they) is a white settl
 er in Tkaronto/Toronto\, and is the author of fifteen books and chapbooks\
 , including Encampment: Resistance\, Grace\, and an Unhoused Community\, w
 hich was awarded the 2025 Toronto Book Award\, and Girls Fall Down (2008)\
 , which was shortlisted for the Toronto Book Award and chosen as the One B
 ook Toronto in 2012. Helwig is a long-time social justice activist\, and a
 lso an Anglican priest\, and has been the rector of the Church of St. Step
 hen-in-the-Fields since 2013.\nBryan Mark is a PhD candidate in the Depart
 ment of Geography and Planning at the University of Toronto. He is an urba
 n geographer who studies contemporary urban cultures. Mark is interested i
 n consumption\, neighbourhood gentrification\, and the mediatization of pl
 ace. His SSHRC-funded doctoral research examines the urban geographies of 
 social media influencers and algorithmic content curation in Toronto. Mark
 's work has also traced the retail gentrification of Ossington Avenue in w
 est downtown Toronto through a cultural and digital critique of an ice-cre
 am boutique.
LOCATION:Koffler Gallery
URL:https://www.blogto.com/events/panel-discussion-torontos-urban-nature-a
 b-uses-toronto/
X-SOURCE:blogTO
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
SUMMARY:Peace Concert
DTSTART;TZID=America/Toronto:20260516T140000
DTEND;TZID=America/Toronto:20260516T160000
UID:blogto-233323@blogto.com
ATTACH;FMTTYPE=image/jpeg:https://blogto-production2-baselayer-display.blo
 gto.com/events/2026/04/08/original_image6e9a57b9-d645-4815-95af-31736bbe53
 ee.jpg
DESCRIPTION:A free concert for peace\, musicians will share their peace-in
 spired music. An added bonus - this will also be the debut launch of the C
 D\, "Afro-Métis Anthem"\, a Toronto Arts Council project led by one of Ca
 nada's literary greats\, poet\, professor and spoken word artist Dr. Georg
 e Elliott Clarke\, and involving musicians from Halifax\, Ottawa\, Nashvil
 le\, and Toronto. An afternoon of entertainment and refreshments\, we will
  be collecting monetary donations in support of the global work of Doctors
  Without Borders/Médecins sans Frontières (MSF) Canada\, bringing doctor
